Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. A control system comprising: a communication interface configured to receive image data from a first instrument that is configured to access an anatomical site via a first access path, the image data representative of the anatomical site and a second instrument that is configured to access the anatomical site via a second access path; and control circuitry communicatively coupled to the communication interface and configured to: cause a visual representation of the image data to be displayed in a user interface; receive a first directional input signal from an input device; determine an orientation of the first instrument relative to the second instrument; and control movement of the second instrument based at least in part on the first directional input signal and the orientation of the first instrument relative to the second instrument. 2. The control system of claim 1, wherein: the first directional input signal is associated with a first direction relative to the input device, the first direction being associated with a first horizontal component; and the control circuitry is configured to: determine to control the second instrument in an inverted control mode; and based at least in part on the inverted control mode, control the second instrument to move in a second direction relative to a frame of reference for the second instrument, the second direction being associated with a second horizontal component that has an opposite sign to the first horizontal component. 3. The control system of claim 2, wherein the frame of reference for the second instrument comprises at least one of a control frame for the second instrument or a coordinate frame for the second instrument. 4. The control system of claim 1, wherein: the first directional input signal is associated with a first direction relative to the input device, the first direction being associated with a first horizontal component; and the control circuitry is configured to: determine to control the second instrument in a direct control mode; and based at least in part on the direct control mode, control the second instrument to move in a second direction relative to a frame of reference for the second instrument, the second direction being associated with a second horizontal component that has a same sign as the first horizontal component. 5. The control system of claim 1, wherein: the first directional input signal is associated with a first direction relative to the input device, the first direction being associated with a first horizontal component; and the control circuitry is configured to: determine to control the second instrument in an inverted control mode; based at least in part on the inverted control mode, control the second instrument to move in a second direction relative to a frame of reference for the second instrument, the second direction being associated with a second horizontal component that has an opposite sign to the first horizontal component; determine to control the second instrument in a direct control mode; 

 receive a second directional input signal from the input device, the second directional input signal being associated with a third direction relative to the input device, the third direction being associated with a third horizontal component; and based at least in part on the direct control mode, control the second instrument to move a fourth direction relative to the frame of reference for the second instrument, the fourth direction being associated with a fourth horizontal component that has a same sign as the third horizontal component. 6. The control system of claim 1, wherein: the first directional input signal is based at least in part on input received via a directional control on the input device; the control circuitry is configured to: determine to control the second instrument in an inverted control mode; based on the directional control being associated with insertion, control the second instrument to be retracted; and based on the directional control being associated with retraction, control the second instrument to be inserted. 7. The control system of claim 1, wherein the control circuitry is configured to: determine a control mode from among a plurality of control modes based at least in part on the orientation of the first instrument relative to the second instrument; and control the movement of the second instrument based at least in part on the control mode. 8. A system comprising: a first robotic manipulator configured to manipulate a direct access instrument at a target anatomical site; 

 a second robotic manipulator configured to manipulate a percutaneous access instrument at the target anatomical site; a user input device including a directional control, the user input device being configured to receive user input via the directional control and generate a first directional input signal based at least in part on the user input; and control circuitry communicatively coupled to the first robotic manipulator, the second robotic manipulator, and the user input device, the control circuitry being configured to: receive image data from the direct access instrument, the image data representing at least a portion of the percutaneous access instrument; generate user interface data representing the image data; determine an orientation of the direct access instrument relative to the percutaneous access instrument; and control the second robotic manipulator based at least in part on the first directional input signal and the orientation of the direct access instrument relative to the percutaneous access instrument. 9. The system of claim 8, wherein: the first directional input signal is associated with a first direction relative to the user input device, the first direction being associated with a first horizontal or vertical component; and the control circuitry is configured to control the second robotic manipulator to move the percutaneous access instrument in a second direction relative to a frame of reference for the percutaneous access instrument based at least in part on an inverted control mode, the second direction being associated with a second horizontal or vertical component that has an opposite sign to the first horizontal or vertical component. 10. The system of claim 9, wherein the control circuitry is further configured to determine the inverted control mode based on at least one of input received via a user interface or input received via the user input device. 11. The system of claim 9, wherein the control circuitry is further configured to: determine the inverted control mode based at least in part on the orientation of the direct access instrument relative to the percutaneous access instrument. 12. The system of claim 9, wherein the first horizontal or vertical direction is left or right. 13. The system of claim 8, wherein: the first directional input signal is associated with a first direction relative to the user input device, the first direction being associated with a first horizontal or vertical component; and the control circuitry is configured to control the second robotic manipulator to move the percutaneous access instrument in a second direction relative to a frame of reference for the second instrument, the second direction being associated with a second horizontal or vertical component that has a same sign as the first horizontal or vertical component. 14. The system of claim 8, wherein the control circuitry is further configured to: receive an input signal indicating to switch control to the direct access instrument; based at least in part on the input signal, configure the system to control the direct access instrument; receive, from the user input device, a second directional input signal; and control the direct access instrument based at least in part on the second directional input signal. 15. The system of claim 8, wherein the direct access instrument comprises an endoscope and the percutaneous access instrument comprises a catheter. 16. A method comprising: receiving, by control circuitry, image data from an endoscope that is configured to access an anatomical site via a first access path, the image data representing at least a portion of a catheter that is configured to access the anatomical site via a second access path; displaying a visual representation of the image data in a user interface; receiving, by the control circuitry and from an input device, a first directional input signal; determining an orientation of the endoscope relative to the catheter; and controlling, by the control circuitry, movement of the catheter based at least in part on the first directional input signal and the orientation of the endoscope relative to the catheter. 17. The method of claim 16, further comprising: determining an inverted control mode for the catheter; wherein the first directional input signal is associated with a first direction relative to the input device, the first direction being associated with a first horizontal component; and wherein the controlling movement of the catheter is based at least in part on the inverted control mode, the catheter being controlled to move in a second direction relative to a frame of reference for the catheter, the second direction being associated with a second horizontal component that has an opposite sign to the first horizontal component. 18. The method of claim 17, further comprising: receiving, via at least one of the input device or the user interface, input indicating the inverted control mode; wherein the determining the inverted control mode is based at least in part on the input. 19. The method of claim 17, wherein the determining the inverted control mode is based at least in part on the orientation of the endoscope relative to the catheter. 20. The method of claim 17, further comprising: determining a direct control mode for the catheter; receiving, from the input device, a second directional input signal that is associated with a third direction relative to the input device, the third direction being associated with a third horizontal component; and controlling movement of the catheter based at least in part on the direct control mode, the catheter being controlled to move in a fourth direction relative to the frame of reference for the catheter, the fourth direction being associated with a fourth horizontal component that has a same sign as the third horizontal component. 21. The method of claim 16, further comprising: receiving an input signal indicating to switch control to the endoscope; receiving, from the input device, a second directional input signal; and controlling movement of the endoscope based at least in part on the input signal and the second directional input signal. 22. The method of claim 16, wherein the first access path comprises a natural lumen in a patient and the second access path comprises a percutaneous access path in the patient. 23. One or more non-transitory computer-readable media storing computer- executable instructions that, when executed by control circuitry, cause the control circuitry to perform operations comprising: receiving image data from an endoscope that is configured to access an anatomical site via a first access path, the image data representing at least a portion of a catheter that is configured to access the anatomical site via a second access path; causing a visual representation of the image data to be displayed in a user interface; 

 receiving, from an input device, a first directional input signal; and controlling movement of the catheter based at least in part on the first directional input signal and an orientation of the endoscope relative to the catheter. 24. The one or more non-transitory computer-readable media of claim 23, wherein the operations further comprise: determining a first control mode for the catheter; wherein the first directional input signal is associated with a first direction relative to the input device, the first direction being associated with a first horizontal component; and wherein the controlling movement of the catheter is based at least in part on the first control mode, the catheter being controlled to move in a second direction relative to a frame of reference for the catheter, the second direction being associated with a second horizontal component that has an opposite sign to the first horizontal component. 25. The one or more non-transitory computer-readable media of claim 24, wherein the frame of reference for the catheter comprises at least one of a control frame for the catheter or a coordinate frame for the catheter. 26. The one or more non-transitory computer-readable media of claim 24, wherein the determining the first control mode is based at least in part on the orientation of the endoscope relative to the catheter. 27. The one or more non-transitory computer-readable media of claim 24, wherein the operations further comprise: determining a second control mode for the catheter; receiving, from the input device a second directional input signal that is associated with a third direction relative to the input device, the third direction being associated with a third horizontal component; and controlling movement of the catheter based at least in part on the second control mode, the catheter being controlled to move in a fourth direction relative 

 to the frame of reference for the catheter, the fourth direction being associated with a fourth horizontal component that has a same sign as the third horizontal component. 28. The one or more non-transitory computer-readable media of claim 23, wherein the operations further comprise: receiving an input signal indicating to switch control to the endoscope; receiving, from the input device, a second directional input signal; and controlling movement of the endoscope based at least in part on the input signal and the second directional input signal. 29. The one or more non-transitory computer-readable media of claim 23, wherein the first access path comprises a natural lumen in a patient and the second access path comprises a percutaneous access path in the patient. 30. The one or more non-transitory computer-readable media of claim 23, wherein the cavity comprises a cavity within a kidney.
